CARBON-FIRST INTELLIGENCE: A MATHEMATICAL AND ARCHITECTURAL FRAMEWORK FOR INTRINSIC BIOLOGICAL SCALING

Ouadi Maakoul


ABSTRACT

The prevailing paradigm of intelligence development assumes a direct proportionality between cognitive capacity and externally sourced computational resources—silicon area, energy throughput, and parameter count. This dissertation challenges that assumption at its axiomatic foundation. We propose that intelligence scales along two orthogonal axes: External Expansion (the silicon trajectory) and Intrinsic Deepening (the biological trajectory). We formalize this distinction through the derivation of the Intrinsic Intelligence Scaling Law (IISL), a power-law relationship defined as:

I = k \cdot \frac{B^{\alpha} \cdot C^{\beta}}{E^{\gamma}}

where I represents effective intelligence, B is a composite index of structural biological integration, C is a measure of conscious causal coherence (quantified via Integrated Information Theory 4.0), and E is the thermodynamic energy expenditure. The exponents \alpha \approx 0.75, \beta \approx 1.35, and \gamma \approx 0.4 are derived from comparative connectomics, clinical Perturbational Complexity Index (PCI) data, and documented energy efficiency gaps between biological and silicon systems (10^4–10^6\times).

This dissertation provides the complete mathematical infrastructure for eight engineering pillars designed to manipulate the IISL variables without violating thermodynamic or homeostatic constraints: (1) Activity-gated epigenetic neuroplasticity, (2) Spectral expansion of the sensorium via engineered opsins, (3) Radiation-hardened genomic architecture via tardigrade-derived proteins, (4) Maximization of causal integration (\Phi), (5) Mitochondrial energetic optimization, (6) Glial lactate shuttle engineering, (7) Interoceptive precision enhancement, and (8) Chronobiological temporal architecture tuning. Each pillar is presented with coupled differential equations governing its dynamics, a state-space model of its failure modes, and a detailed molecular architecture for its implementation via somatic, reversible CRISPRa circuits.

A central contribution of this work is the formalization of Substrate Partition Failure (SPF) —a metabolic down-regulation cascade triggered by cognitive offloading to external silicon systems—which demonstrates that hybrid architectures are thermodynamically unstable attractors. The framework establishes a rigorous, falsifiable roadmap for directed intrinsic evolution, culminating in the design specification for Homo Intellectus: a biological configuration defined by eight measurable parameters achievable through somatic intervention.

Keywords: Intrinsic Intelligence Scaling, Integrated Information Theory, CRISPRa, Substrate Partition Failure, Biological Superintelligence, Directed Evolution, Thermodynamics of Computation.

