3.6 Formal Proof of the Substrate Partition Failure (SPF) Instability

Definition 3.5 (Hybrid System). A hybrid system H consists of a biological component S_{bio} and a silicon component S_{sil}, coupled via an interface I with information transfer rate R_{trans}.

Definition 3.6 (Substrate Partition Failure). SPF occurs when the loss of S_{sil} causes a functional deficit in S_{bio} that exceeds the deficit S_{bio} would exhibit in the complete absence of any prior augmentation.

Theorem 3.7 (SPF Instability). For any hybrid system H where S_{sil} performs a fraction \phi > \phi_{crit} of the total cognitive load for a duration \tau > \tau_{crit}, the post-disconnection intelligence I_{post} satisfies:

I_{post} < I_{pre-augment} \quad \text{and} \quad \frac{dI_{post}}{dt} < 0 \text{ for } t \in [0, \tau_{recovery}]

where \tau_{recovery} \gg \tau.

Proof. The biological component adapts its synaptic and metabolic infrastructure according to a use-dependent plasticity rule:

\frac{dB}{dt} = \eta (L_{bio} - L_{crit}) B

where L_{bio} is the cognitive load on S_{bio}. Under augmentation, L_{bio} = (1-\phi)L_{total} < L_{crit}. Thus B decays exponentially:

B(t) = B_0 e^{-\lambda (\phi) t}

with \lambda(\phi) > 0 for \phi > \phi_{crit}.

Upon disconnection, the required load L_{total} is imposed on a substrate with reduced capacity B(t_{disconnect}) < B_0. The resulting performance I_{post} is bounded by:

I_{post} \leq k \frac{B(t_{disconnect})^{\alpha} C^{\beta}}{E^{\gamma}} < k \frac{B_0^{\alpha} C^{\beta}}{E^{\gamma}} = I_{pre-augment}

The recovery time \tau_{recovery} is the time for B to return to B_0 via the slow growth dynamics, which is much longer than the decay timescale. \square

