CHAPTER 5: PILLAR 2 — INPUT/OUTPUT: THE UNIVERSAL SENSORIUM

5.1 Introduction: The Spectral Constraint

Human vision is restricted to the narrow band of electromagnetic radiation between approximately 400 nm (violet) and 700 nm (red). This constraint is not a physical necessity—it is an evolutionary accident. The vertebrate common ancestor was a tetrachromat with four distinct opsin classes, including sensitivity to ultraviolet (UV) light (Bowmaker, 2008). In the mammalian lineage, the UV-sensitive opsin gene (SWS1) was silenced, and the long-wavelength-sensitive (LWS) and medium-wavelength-sensitive (MWS) opsins diverged to provide trichromacy in primates. Birds, reptiles, and many fish retain tetrachromatic vision, and some snakes possess infrared (IR)-sensitive pit organs.

This chapter presents the mathematical and architectural foundation for Pillar 2: somatic expansion of the human sensorium to include UV (300–400 nm) and near-infrared (NIR, 700–1400 nm) perception. This directly increases the connection diversity component B_{div} of the IISL's B variable by expanding the Shannon entropy of input channels.

5.2 Biophysics of Phototransduction

5.2.1 Opsin Kinetics and Spectral Tuning

Vertebrate phototransduction begins when a photon isomerizes the 11-cis-retinal chromophore bound to an opsin protein. This triggers a G-protein cascade culminating in the closure of cyclic nucleotide-gated (CNG) channels and hyperpolarization of the photoreceptor.

The spectral sensitivity of an opsin is determined by the amino acid residues lining the chromophore-binding pocket. The peak absorption wavelength \lambda_{max} is governed by electrostatic interactions that tune the energy gap between ground and excited states of retinal.

The kinetics of the photoresponse are characterized by the deactivation time constant \tau_{off}, which is the time for the activated opsin (metarhodopsin II) to be phosphorylated and bound by arrestin. Fast opsins (e.g., mouse cone opsin) have \tau_{off} \sim 20 ms, while slow opsins (e.g., channelrhodopsin-2) have \tau_{off} \sim 10–100 ms. For high-temporal-resolution vision, \tau_{off} < 5 ms is desirable.

5.2.2 Mathematical Model of Phototransduction

The light-induced change in photoreceptor current I_{photo} is modeled by a cascade of differential equations (modified from Nikonov et al., 2005):

Activation:

\frac{d[Rh^*]}{dt} = \sigma(\lambda) \cdot \Phi(\lambda) \cdot [Rh] - k_{act} \cdot [Rh^*]

where:

· [Rh^*] is the concentration of activated rhodopsin.
· \sigma(\lambda) is the absorption cross-section at wavelength \lambda.
· \Phi(\lambda) is the photon flux.
· k_{act} is the deactivation rate (1/\tau_{off}).

Transducin Activation:

\frac{d[G^*]}{dt} = k_G \cdot [Rh^*] \cdot [G] - k_{G,off} \cdot [G^*]

PDE Activation and cGMP Hydrolysis:

\frac{d[cGMP]}{dt} = \alpha_{GC} - (\beta_{dark} + \beta_{PDE} \cdot [PDE^*]) \cdot [cGMP]

Channel Current:

I_{photo} = I_{max} \cdot \frac{[cGMP]^{n_H}}{K_{cGMP}^{n_H} + [cGMP]^{n_H}}

with Hill coefficient n_H \approx 3.

5.2.3 Spectral Crosstalk and Channel Capacity

When multiple opsin classes are co-expressed in the same photoreceptor, their spectral sensitivities overlap, causing spectral crosstalk. The information capacity of a single photoreceptor is limited by the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) and the bandwidth of temporal modulation.

The mutual information between the light spectrum S(\lambda) and the photoreceptor response R is:

I(S; R) = \int_{\lambda} \int_{R} p(S, R) \log_2 \frac{p(S, R)}{p(S) p(R)} dR d\lambda

Crosstalk reduces I(S; R) because different spectra produce indistinguishable responses. To maximize information, the opsins must be spectrally orthogonal and expressed in separate photoreceptor populations (or separate retinal regions) that project to distinct cortical columns.

5.3 Design of Chimeric UV and NIR Opsins

5.3.1 UV-Sensitive Opsin (UVS)

The human genome retains a silenced copy of the SWS1 (short-wavelength-sensitive 1) opsin gene. Reactivation via CRISPRa can restore UV sensitivity, but the native protein has \lambda_{max} \approx 360 nm and slow kinetics (\tau_{off} \approx 50 ms).

Chimeric Design:
We propose a fusion of the UVS spectral tuning residues with the fast kinetics scaffold of ReaChR (red-activatable channelrhodopsin, \tau_{off} \approx 3 ms) or ChroME (\tau_{off} \approx 4 ms). The chimera retains the UV absorption peak while achieving rapid deactivation.

Spectral Tuning Mutations:

· Replace residues 86, 90, 93, 113, 118 in the retinal binding pocket with those from human SWS1.
· Introduce F86Y, T93P, A118G to shift \lambda_{max} to ~360 nm.

Predicted Performance:

· \lambda_{max} = 360 \pm 10 nm
· \tau_{off} < 5 ms
· Peak current: 500–1000 pA at saturating UV.

5.3.2 Near-Infrared-Sensitive Opsin (NIRS)

No native human opsin is sensitive beyond ~700 nm. We must engineer a synthetic NIR opsin. Two strategies exist:

1. Directed Evolution of Channelrhodopsin: Starting from the red-shifted variant ReaChR (\lambda_{max} \approx 590 nm), iterative mutagenesis and screening can shift absorption further into the NIR. However, the energy of NIR photons is insufficient to isomerize retinal efficiently, imposing a fundamental limit.
2. Two-Photon Excitation: Co-expression of a two-photon absorbing chromophore (e.g., a porphyrin derivative) that absorbs two NIR photons and transfers energy to retinal via FRET. This is speculative but theoretically viable.

Proposed NIR Opsin (NIR-ChR):

· Scaffold: ChR2 with C128S mutation (slower kinetics but higher sensitivity).
· Chromophore substitution: Replace retinal with A2-retinal (3,4-dehydroretinal), which red-shifts absorption by ~20–30 nm.
· Additional mutations: E123T, H134R to further red-shift and accelerate kinetics.

Predicted Performance:

· \lambda_{max} = 650–700 nm (near the limit of retinal isomerization).
· For deeper NIR (700–1400 nm), two-photon mechanisms are required.

5.3.3 Avoiding Phototoxicity

UV and intense visible light can damage retinal tissue via photochemical reactions. The phototoxicity threshold is:

\Phi_{safe}(\lambda) = \frac{E_{damage}}{\sigma_{damage}(\lambda) \cdot t_{exposure}}

where E_{damage} is the energy required to cause cellular damage (~1 J/cm² for UV). We incorporate a light-gated safety switch:

· Inducible Caspase-9 (iCasp9): Fused to a light-oxygen-voltage (LOV) domain. Upon exposure to damaging light levels, the LOV domain dimerizes, activating caspase-9 and triggering apoptosis of the overexposed photoreceptor. This is a fail-deadly safety mechanism for extreme overload.

5.4 Cortical Remapping Protocol: The Chromatic Unmixing Task

5.4.1 The Problem of Adult Cortical Plasticity

The adult visual cortex has limited capacity to segregate novel spectral channels. Simply adding a new photoreceptor class results in perceptual confusion—UV signals are interpreted as blue, and NIR signals are not consciously perceived. Cortical remapping requires targeted training that forces the cortex to assign new representations.

5.4.2 VR-Based Chromatic Unmixing Protocol

We design a 4–6 week virtual reality (VR) training paradigm:

Phase 1 (Weeks 1–2): NIR-to-Visible Translation

· NIR images are presented as a false-color overlay on the visible scene (e.g., NIR appears as green).
· The subject learns to associate NIR "color" with object properties (e.g., vegetation appears bright in NIR).

Phase 2 (Weeks 3–4): Graduated Fading

· The NIR-to-visible translation is gradually reduced in opacity.
· The subject must rely increasingly on the native NIR signal.

Phase 3 (Weeks 5–6): Chromatic Unmixing Task

· Objects are presented that differ only in NIR reflectance (invisible to normal vision).
· The subject receives real-time neurofeedback (EEG/fMRI) that rewards correct NIR-based discrimination.

5.4.3 Mathematical Model of Perceptual Learning

The cortical representation of a novel spectral channel evolves according to a competitive learning rule:

\frac{d\mathbf{w}_k}{dt} = \eta \cdot h_{k, winner} \cdot (\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{w}_k)

where \mathbf{w}_k is the weight vector of cortical column k, \mathbf{x} is the input pattern, and h is a neighborhood function. Over training, columns that respond to NIR inputs become spatially segregated from those responding to visible light.

Proposition 5.1 (Convergence of Chromatic Unmixing). Given sufficient training trials T > T_{crit} with distinct NIR patterns, the cortical weight vectors converge to a configuration where the mutual information between NIR input and column identity is maximized.

Proof. The competitive learning rule minimizes the reconstruction error \|\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{w}_{winner}\|^2. For orthogonal input dimensions (e.g., visible vs. NIR), the weight vectors align with the principal components of the input distribution. Since NIR patterns are statistically independent of visible patterns (by design of the training stimuli), distinct columns emerge. \square

5.5 Architectural Specifications

5.5.1 AAV Vector for Retinal Delivery

Vector for UVS Reactivation:

· Promoter: GRM6 (metabotropic glutamate receptor 6) — specific to ON bipolar cells, preserving retinal circuitry.
· Transgene: dCas9-VP64 under GRM6 promoter.
· sgRNA: U6-sgSWS1 targeting the silenced SWS1 promoter.
· Payload: ~4.5 kb (feasible in single AAV).

Vector for NIR Opsin:

· Promoter: GRM6 or RHO (rhodopsin) for rod-specific expression.
· Transgene: NIR-ChR (1.0 kb) + fluorescent reporter.
· Payload: ~2.5 kb.

5.5.2 Chromophore Availability

A2-retinal is not endogenously synthesized in humans. We propose oral supplementation of 3,4-dehydroretinol (vitamin A2), which is converted to A2-retinal in the retinal pigment epithelium. Pharmacokinetic modeling ensures steady-state levels.

5.5.3 Safety Monitoring

· Electroretinography (ERG): Monitor photoreceptor health weekly.
· Optical Coherence Tomography (OCT): Assess retinal thickness and signs of inflammation.
· Visual Acuity Testing: Ensure no loss of native vision.

5.6 Falsifiable Predictions (Hypothesis H2)

H2: CRISPRa reactivation of UVS opsin in adult human iPSC-derived retinal organoids will produce:

1. Functional UV-responsive photoreceptors confirmed by ERG response to 350–400 nm stimuli absent in non-CRISPRa controls.
2. Immunohistochemistry confirming UVS opsin protein expression in outer segment structures.
3. Calcium imaging confirming UV-triggered phototransduction cascade activation.

H2b (In Vivo Extension): In non-human primates, NIR opsin expression plus 6-week VR training will yield behavioral discrimination of NIR-only stimuli at >80% accuracy, with no degradation of native color vision.

5.7 Summary

Pillar 2 expands the sensory bandwidth of the biological system by adding UV and NIR perception. The design combines CRISPRa reactivation of silenced opsins, engineering of fast-kinetics chimeras, and a rigorous cortical remapping protocol. This directly increases B_{div}, the connection diversity component of the IISL's B variable, by increasing the Shannon entropy of sensory input channels.

